WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.640 --> 00:00:12.400
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. Today we're&nbsp;
going to talk about arithmetic with Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:17.640
numbers. We're going to talk about addition,&nbsp;
subtraction, and multiplication, and we'll have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:17.640 --> 00:00:23.320
a few things to say that are quite interesting&nbsp;
for primary school education. Let's start off with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:30.440
the simplest one: addition. Naively, we have two&nbsp;
strings of ones, which are for us natural numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:36.120
To add them, we just put them together in the&nbsp;
obvious way. The second level of complexity is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.120 --> 00:00:42.200
with Roman numerals, where we peeled off some 10,&nbsp;
which we write as X's. So we recognize this number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:49.160
as 10, 10, 1—that's 21—plus the other one, 15. And&nbsp;
to add them with Roman numerals, we just put all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:57.320
the X's together and we put all the ones together&nbsp;
to give us 36. With Hindu-Arabic notation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.320 --> 00:01:06.800
we represent this by 21 (2 tens, 1 one) and this&nbsp;
by 15 (1 ten and 5 ones). To add them, we can put&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:14.760
them on top of each other like this, and when&nbsp;
we add the ones and we add the tens, we get 36.

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:21.080
So it gets a little bit more complicated if we&nbsp;
have bigger numbers. So here is another example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:30.200
which turns out to be 16 plus 19. In Roman&nbsp;
numerals, we put them together, we get two X's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.200 --> 00:01:36.600
(20), and then we have a string of ones. But we&nbsp;
have agreed with the Roman numeral notation that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:36.600 --> 00:01:42.640
we're not going to allow 10 or more strings.&nbsp;
Whenever we have 10 or more of a certain kind,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.640 --> 00:01:47.760
we exchange it for a higher denomination.&nbsp;
So here we have a string of ones,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:52.240
we peel off a 10 and replace it&nbsp;
with another X. It's an exchange,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.240 --> 00:02:00.960
and so we end up with XXX and 5 ones—that's 35. So&nbsp;
how does it work in Hindu-Arabic notation? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:08.400
we put the 16 on top of the 19, we add the&nbsp;
6 and 9, we get 15. And the corresponding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:08.400 --> 00:02:15.000
thing here is to put five ones here and to peel&nbsp;
the other 10 ones off and write it as a single&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:25.560
10. So you're adding one 10 to the tens column,&nbsp;
and then we add the tens to get 35 altogether.

00:02:25.560 --> 00:02:34.680
Another example: same idea. Let's say we have&nbsp;
247 + 385. We start with the ones: 7 + 5 is 12,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:34.680 --> 00:02:41.120
which we write as 2 ones and 1 ten. Then&nbsp;
altogether, the tens, we have 13 tens,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:41.120 --> 00:02:48.320
which we write as 3 tens + 10 tens. And that&nbsp;
10 tens is written as 1 hundred and goes in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:48.320 --> 00:02:56.840
the hundreds column. And altogether, we have 6&nbsp;
hundreds, so we have 632 as the final answer.

00:02:56.840 --> 00:02:59.840
Now let's have a look at subtraction,&nbsp;
the inverse operation to addition.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:06.280
If we have this number and we want to subtract&nbsp;
this number, what it means is that effectively&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.280 --> 00:03:12.080
we're peeling off a number of ones just equal to&nbsp;
the number there. So we're going to peel off these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:17.400
four ones, and whatever we have left over is the&nbsp;
final answer. In terms of Roman numerals, we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.400 --> 00:03:26.520
this minus this, and it's easy to see that 7 ones&nbsp;
minus 4 ones is 3 ones, so we end up with 13. In&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:36.822
terms of Hindu-Arabic notation, 17 - 4, we write&nbsp;
17 - 4: 7 ones minus 4 ones is 3 ones, and 10&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:36.822 --> 00:03:43.080
tens minus 0 tens is 10 tens, so we get 13. That&nbsp;
mimics what we're doing with the Roman numerals.

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:51.200
Here's a more complicated example where we have&nbsp;
34 - 16. Now to make that subtraction with Roman&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:51.200 --> 00:03:55.640
numerals, we can't quite do it because&nbsp;
we have 4 ones and we need to subtract&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.640 --> 00:04:03.920
6 ones—that doesn't work. So we change one of&nbsp;
the tens here for 10 ones, giving us 14 ones,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.920 --> 00:04:11.080
which we can then subtract 6 from, giving us 8&nbsp;
ones. And we have 2 tens minus 1 ten, which is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:21.320
single ten. What we do with Hindu-Arabic notation&nbsp;
is exactly parallel to this. So we write 34 - 16:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.320 --> 00:04:31.640
4 - 6 doesn't work, so we need to change one of&nbsp;
our tens for 10 ones. Instead of having 3 tens,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.640 --> 00:04:38.600
we now have 2 tens. Instead of having 4 ones, we&nbsp;
now have 14 ones. The actual number that we've got&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:45.840
hasn't changed, just the denominations that are&nbsp;
involved have changed. But now 14 - 6—that works,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:54.200
that gives us 8. And 2 - 1 is 1, so&nbsp;
we have 18 as the answer. And that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:54.200 --> 00:05:00.600
corresponds to what happens in real life.&nbsp;
If I have $34 in three tens and four ones,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:07.440
and you come up and ask me for $16, then I'm going&nbsp;
to have to change one of my tens for 10 ones,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:07.440 --> 00:05:14.120
perhaps through some third party, in order to&nbsp;
be able to peel off the right money for you.

00:05:14.120 --> 00:05:20.760
Now last year, my daughter in school learned a&nbsp;
different way of doing subtraction which I do not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:29.400
approve of. This is the way she does subtraction:&nbsp;
34 - 16. Okay, the 4 - 6 doesn't work,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.400 --> 00:05:37.120
so we're going to add 10 ones for 14, and then to&nbsp;
compensate for that, instead of subtracting 1 ten,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:37.120 --> 00:05:48.440
we're going to subtract 2 tens. So 14 - 6 is&nbsp;
8, and 3 - 2 is 1. We get the same answer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:54.240
but it's much less intuitively clear what's&nbsp;
going on with this method because it doesn't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.240 --> 00:05:59.840
correspond to what we actually do in real&nbsp;
life. If I have 34 and I want to give you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:59.840 --> 00:06:05.320
16, this corresponds to suddenly getting&nbsp;
10 more from somewhere and then you take&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:11.040
10 more to compensate—that doesn't happen in&nbsp;
real life. It's a good example of where pure&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:16.040
mathematicians can have something to say&nbsp;
about primary school education. If your&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:20.880
child is being taught this way, I don't&nbsp;
think they're being taught the right way.

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:26.360
Now let's have a look at multiplication. The first&nbsp;
thing that children have to do is to learn the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:26.360 --> 00:06:32.320
multiplication table. So here is part of the usual&nbsp;
table, and let's assume that we've memorized this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:32.320 --> 00:06:38.200
perhaps up to 10x10 or 12x12. I also remind&nbsp;
you of a few of our basic laws: there's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.200 --> 00:06:46.840
associative law for multiplication written in&nbsp;
our abbreviated fashion. So a stands for a * b,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:46.840 --> 00:06:53.120
and here are the two distributive laws that we've&nbsp;
talked about before. And here is a fancier version&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.120 --> 00:06:58.720
of the distributive law, where we have one&nbsp;
term with two numbers added up times another&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:04.360
term with another two terms added together.&nbsp;
The result is four different multiplications:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:04.360 --> 00:07:12.920
a * c plus a * d plus b * c plus b * d. So that's&nbsp;
a combination of these two distributive laws,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:19.480
and it's very important for understanding how&nbsp;
we actually implement multiplication by hand.

00:07:19.480 --> 00:07:31.720
So let's see what happens if we multiply 234 *&nbsp;
3. 234 is really 2 * 100 + 3 * 10 + 4. When we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.720 --> 00:07:38.280
multiply by 3, we're really using the distributive&nbsp;
law. The 3 is multiplied by this term to give 600,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.280 --> 00:07:44.400
and also by this term to give 90, and 3 *&nbsp;
4 (this term) gives 12. And then we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.400 --> 00:07:53.640
to add up those three things to give us 702.&nbsp;
And by hand, what we do is we write 234 * 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:59.640
and then there are three separate multiplications&nbsp;
that are really involved: 3 * 4 is 12;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:07.040
3 times this 3 really represents 30, so 3 times&nbsp;
that 30 is really 90; and this 2 represents&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:14.520
200, so 3 * 200 is 600. So there are three&nbsp;
things to be added up. We add them up in columns,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.520 --> 00:08:21.520
and that's a sure-fire and good way of teaching&nbsp;
multiplication to students to begin with. Later&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:21.520 --> 00:08:26.520
on, if necessary and they're proficient, you&nbsp;
can do this all in one step. But there's nothing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.520 --> 00:08:33.360
embarrassing about just doing multiplication this&nbsp;
way step by step. That way you understand that the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:41.360
distributive law is really what's happening, and&nbsp;
you have as many operations as you do terms here.

00:08:41.360 --> 00:08:47.320
Let's have a look at a slightly more complicated&nbsp;
example: 56 * 37. This is an example where we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:47.320 --> 00:08:54.560
implicitly using this law here. So there are&nbsp;
really four separate multiplications going on:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.560 --> 00:09:05.560
7 * 6 is 42; 7 * 5 (well, this 5 represents&nbsp;
50, so 7 * 50 is 350); this 3 * 6 (well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:14.640
that's really 30 * 6—that's 180); and 30&nbsp;
* 50 is 1,500. So there are really those&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:14.640 --> 00:09:21.560
four separate multiplications, and then we add&nbsp;
them all up using a bit of carrying: 4, 5, 8,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:21.560 --> 00:09:29.560
17 (so there's a one that goes up there),&nbsp;
then 10 (one that goes up there), and 2.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.560 --> 00:09:35.080
So, although better students can do this&nbsp;
in two lines, there's nothing wrong with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:43.080
weaker students being taught this very&nbsp;
sure-fire methodical way of doing it.

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:46.920
Next time, we're going to talk about the&nbsp;
trickiest operation, which is, of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:46.920 --> 00:09:50.800
division. And we're going to have some&nbsp;
interesting things to say about long&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:50.800 --> 00:09:59.320
division. I hope you'll join me for that.&nbsp;
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:09:59.320 --> 00:10:02.837
Let me know if you need any further assistance!

